{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4f3f7223-cce4-45f7-b30c-e83867018c14","content":"I don't see the project at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the most common approach):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Your server must communicate over **stdio** (reading from stdin, writing to stdout). The official [C# MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/csharp-sdk) handles this.\n- Use `dotnet run --project` so it builds and runs in one step.\n- If you publish the app instead, replace the command with the path to the compiled binary.\n- For a **published** build, it would look like:\n  ```json\n  \"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n  ```\n\nAfter saving, restart VS Code or run **\"MCP: List Servers\"** from the command palette to verify the server is detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a24bf394-31a6-41bc-86b5-5c2a10f0d567","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user said they built it. Regardless, I can still tell them how to configure mcp.json. Let me provide the configuration guidance.","outputTokens":364,"requestId":"F042:1A905D:126965C:14C5DAA:69F94126"},"id":"638e57e2-f948-4521-8566-8f778f44ba62","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:00:32.726Z","parentId":"74879355-9c95-4e78-b195-b7f882f90aa4"}
